🧠 2) DSA — TWO POINTER TECHNIQUE
🔥 Core Idea

Two pointers = efficient traversal of data with minimal passes

🧠 Deep Understanding
✔ Why it works

Instead of:

Nested loops → O(n²)

Use:

Two pointers → O(n)
🔥 Example
def pair_sum(arr, target):
    left, right = 0, len(arr) - 1

    while left < right:
        s = arr[left] + arr[right]
        if s == target:
            return True
        elif s < target:
            left += 1
        else:
            right -= 1
⚙️ Real-Time Usage
✔ Trading Systems
match buy/sell orders
✔ Banking
detect duplicate transactions
✔ Data Pipelines
merging sorted streams
🔥 Advanced Patterns
✔ 1. Remove duplicates
# in-place processing
✔ 2. Merge sorted arrays
✔ 3. Partitioning (QuickSort logic)
🧠 GS-Level Answer

👉 “When do you use two pointers?”

💬 Strong Answer:

“I use the two-pointer technique when working with sorted data or when I need to optimize from a quadratic solution to linear time. It is particularly useful for problems like pair sums, duplicate removal, and merging sorted datasets.”

⚠️ Common Mistakes

❌ forgetting sorted condition
❌ wrong pointer movement
❌ infinite loop

⚙️ 3) PRODUCTION — BAD DATA HANDLING (CRITICAL)
🔥 Core Idea

👉 Real systems don’t fail because of logic
👉 They fail because of bad data

🧠 Types of Bad Data
Type	Example
Missing field	amount missing
Invalid type	"abc" instead of number
Corrupt row	broken CSV
Business invalid	negative amount
🔥 Real System Problem
1 bad row → system crash ❌

👉 unacceptable in production

🔥 Handling Strategy
✔ 1. Validate early
if not amount:
    raise ValueError
✔ 2. Use try/except
try:
    process(record)
except Exception:
    continue
✔ 3. Log bad records
logger.error("Bad record", extra={"record": record})
✔ 4. Skip, don’t stop

👉 pipeline must continue

✔ 5. Dead Letter Queue (ADVANCED)

👉 store bad records for later

🔥 Real Production Example
CSV → Read → Validate → Process
               ↓
            Bad Data → Logs / DLQ
🧠 GS-Level Answer

👉 “How do you handle bad data?”

💬 Strong Answer:

“I handle bad data by validating records early and categorizing errors into schema, type, and business errors. I use exception handling to prevent system crashes, log invalid records with sufficient context, and ensure the pipeline continues processing valid data. For critical systems, I store failed records in a dead-letter queue for further analysis.”

⚠️ Common Mistakes

❌ crashing system
❌ ignoring errors
❌ no logging

